  <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    <h2>The Foundation of Modern Upper Materials</h2>
    
    <p>
      Knit textiles have revolutionized footwear upper construction, enabling unprecedented engineering control over mechanical properties, breathability, and comfort. From traditional hand-knit socks to computer-controlled engineered knits, the fundamental loop structure creates flexible, dimensionally stable fabrics.
    </p>

    <h2>Knit Construction Fundamentals</h2>
    
    <h3>Loop Structure</h3>
    <p>
      The fundamental knit unit—the loop—creates the characteristic flexibility and recovery of knit textiles.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Interlocking Loops:</strong> Each loop passes through the previous loop, creating chain-like structure.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Inherent Stretch:</strong> Loop geometry provides natural stretch without elastic fibers.
    </p>

    <h3>Pattern Variation</h3>
    <p>
      Different stitch patterns create varied surface textures, densities, and mechanical properties.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Jersey Knit:</strong> Basic pattern with smooth face and textured back.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Rib Knit:</strong> Vertical ribs created by alternating knit and purl stitches.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Purl Knit:</strong> Transverse ridges from purl stitches on both sides.
    </p>

    <h2>Weft Knitting</h2>
    
    <h3>Flat Knitting</h3>
    <p>
      Flat knitting produces fabric in flat panels, widely used for full鞋面 construction.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Whole Garment Knitting:</strong> Complete upper knitted in one piece without seaming.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Panel Construction:</strong> Flat panels assembled by seaming.
    </p>

    <h3>Circular Knitting</h3>
    <p>
      Circular knitting produces seamless tubular fabric, efficient for high-volume production.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>High Production:</strong> Efficient for commodity textile production.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Limited Shape:</strong> Tubular form requires cutting for complex shapes.
    </p>

    <h2>Engineered Knit Technology</h2>
    
    <h3>Flyknit and Similar Systems</h3>
    <p>
      Engineered knit technologies produce one-piece upper constructions with precisely controlled properties.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Zone Engineering:</strong> Knit structure varies across the upper for optimal performance.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Seamless Construction:</strong> Single-piece knit eliminates traditional stitching.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Material Efficiency:</strong> Only required material is used, reducing waste.
    </p>

    <h3>3D Knit Structures</h3>
    <p>
      Advanced knitting produces true three-dimensional fabric structures.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Volume Knitting:</strong> Creates varying thickness across the surface.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Shape-Knit Elements:</strong> Pre-shaped components require minimal processing.
    </p>

    <h2>Performance Characteristics</h2>
    
    <h3>Mechanical Properties</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Stretch and Recovery:</strong> Knit stretch provides fit accommodation and comfort.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Breathability:</strong> Open structures enable air circulation.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Lightweight:</strong> Minimal material creates lightweight uppers.
    </p>

    <h3>Functional Integration</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Zone-Specific Properties:</strong> Different areas can have different characteristics.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Integrated Support:</strong> Knit structure can provide targeted support.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Moisture Management:</strong> Specialized yarns can enhance moisture wicking.
    </p>

    <h2>China Manufacturing</h2>
    
    <h3>Production Capabilities</h3>
    <p>
      China dominates advanced knit textile production with state-of-the-art equipment.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Equipment Base:</strong> Shima Seiki, Stoll, and Karl Mayer machines widely available.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Technical Expertise:</strong> Extensive workforce experience with engineered knits.
    </p>

    <h3>Sourcing Considerations</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Technical Specifications:</strong> Define precise mechanical property requirements.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Machine Capabilities:</strong> Verify equipment matches design requirements.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Quality Consistency:</strong> Establish control procedures for batch-to-batch consistency.
    </p>
  </div>
